<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL PALACE MUSEUM TO PROMOTE SOUTHERN BRANCH'S EXHIBITIONS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  14 (CNA) 01/14/07  19:15:04 (By Y.L.Kao)
</P>
<P>
The National Palace Museum in suburban Taipei is scheduled to
hold a series of speeches in the coming few months to introduce
the exhibition themes of its southern branch's six permanent
galleries, a spokesman for the museum said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The museum's  southern  branch,  which is currently  under
construction in Taibao in southern Chiayi County, is designed not
only for housing part of the museum's collection of Chinese art
works but also for the promotion of Asian arts and culture,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Under the sponsorship of the Cheng Yang Art and Cultural
Foundation, the museum has invited several renowned researchers
and experts to give lectures concerning the exhibits to be
displayed at the six theme halls, including Hiroko Nishida,
deputy curator of the Nezu Art Museum in Tokyo, Jan. 16-18; Lu
Chenglong, a researcher at the Beijing Palace Museum, Jan. 25-26;
and Huo Hua, a researcher at the Nanjing Museum, Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
The lectures to be held on the museum's fourth floor will cover a
wide variety of topics on Asian tea culture, monochrome porcelain
works, blue-and-white porcelain works, as well as Asian
literature, Buddhism and weaving artifacts, to help the public
gain an in-depth understanding of Asian arts and culture.
</P>
